🚀 Topic: Memory Attributes (SoC / ARM)

👉 These attributes tell the system:

“How should this memory region be treated by cache, interconnect, and CPU?”

🧠 Big Picture First

When CPU accesses memory, it doesn’t just say:

Read/Write address X

👉 It also implicitly uses memory attributes like:

Can I cache it?
Can I delay writes?
Is it shared with others?
🧩 1. Cacheable vs Non-Cacheable
🔹 Cacheable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Data can be stored in cache

⚙️ Behavior
Read → goes to cache (hit/miss logic)
Write → follows write policy (write-back, etc.)
📦 Use cases
Normal data (arrays, variables, stack, heap)
🔥 Key benefit
Fast access
Exploits locality
🔹 Non-Cacheable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Data must NOT be cached

⚙️ Behavior
Every access goes directly to memory
Cache is bypassed
📦 Use cases
DMA buffers
Device memory (MMIO)
Hardware registers
⚠️ Why?

👉 Because caching can cause:

Stale data
Incorrect behavior
🎯 Connection to what you learned

👉 Non-cacheable = similar to:

“No write allocate”
“Always miss” behavior
🧩 2. Bufferable vs Non-Bufferable
🔹 Bufferable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Writes can be temporarily stored (buffered) before going to memory

⚙️ Behavior
CPU writes → goes to write buffer
Memory update may happen later
🔥 Benefit
Improves performance
CPU doesn’t stall
🔹 Non-Bufferable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Writes must go directly to memory (no delay)

⚙️ Behavior
Write completes only when memory is updated
📦 Use cases
Device registers
Control signals
⚠️ Why?

👉 Some operations require:

Immediate visibility
Strict ordering
🧠 Important distinction

👉 Bufferable is about:

Write timing

👉 Cacheable is about:

Where data is stored

🧩 3. Shareable vs Non-Shareable
🔹 Shareable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Memory is shared between multiple agents

Multiple CPU cores
DMA
Devices
⚙️ Behavior
Participates in coherency domain
Requires:
Cache coherency
Synchronization
📦 Use cases
Shared memory in multicore systems
CPU ↔ FPGA buffers
🔹 Non-Shareable
🧠 Meaning

👉 Memory is private to one core

⚙️ Behavior
No coherency needed
Faster access
📦 Use cases
Core-local data
Scratchpad-like usage
🔥 Important Insight

👉 Shareable does NOT mean:

“Automatically coherent”

👉 It means:

“Must be treated as part of coherency system”

🧠 Putting it all together
📦 Example configurations
🟢 Normal RAM (CPU data)
Cacheable     = Yes
Bufferable    = Yes
Shareable     = Yes (in multicore)
🔴 Device Memory (MMIO)
Cacheable     = No
Bufferable    = No
Shareable     = Yes (visible to system)
🟡 DMA Buffer (common case)
Cacheable     = Sometimes No (or managed carefully)
Bufferable    = Yes
Shareable     = Yes
⚠️ Common Bugs (VERY IMPORTANT)
❌ Bug 1: Cacheable DMA buffer

👉 Leads to:

Stale data
Corruption
❌ Bug 2: Bufferable device memory

👉 Leads to:

Writes delayed
Hardware sees wrong state
❌ Bug 3: Wrong shareability

👉 Leads to:

Coherency issues
Hard-to-debug bugs
🎯 Final Mental Model

👉 Think of attributes like:

Attribute	Controls
Cacheable	Use cache or not
Bufferable	Delay writes or not
Shareable	Multi-agent visibility
💡 One-liner (interview ready)

Memory attributes define how memory accesses are handled in terms of caching, buffering, and sharing across agents in a system.

